<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<rdf:RDF
  xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#"
  xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#"
  xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#"
  xmlns:crm="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/"
  xmlns:crmdig="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/"
  xml:base="https://pcomans.github.io/hapi-crm">

  <owl:Ontology rdf:about="https://pcomans.github.io/hapi-crm">
    <owl:versionInfo>Hapi CRM/CRMdig extension manifest, May 2026</owl:versionInfo>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">
      Hapi project's RDFS extensions on top of CIDOC CRM 7.1.3 + CRMdig 5.0.
      Conforms to the standard CIDOC extension idiom: rdfs:subClassOf and
      rdfs:subPropertyOf declarations that narrow within the parent's domain
      and range, never violate. Strict CIDOC readers running RDFS reasoning
      interpret Hapi terms through their declared parents.

      See docs/adr/018-authority-as-claim-graph.md, section "Hapi extension
      manifest", for full context and the rationale for each declaration.

      Pin: this manifest is co-pinned with ADR-018's CRM + CRMdig versions.
      Moves on either pinned spec require re-validating every declaration
      below for continued domain/range conformance under the new spec.
    </rdfs:comment>
  </owl:Ontology>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Classes: matcher provenance (CRMdig-typed)
       ============================================================ -->

  <rdfs:Class rdf:about="#MatcherRun">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Matcher run</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/D10_Software_Execution"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A specific execution of a Hapi matcher: a software program runs over source data as a single task, producing derived assertions. IS-A chain: hapi:MatcherRun ⊂ crmdig:D10 Software Execution ⊂ D7 Digital Machine Event ⊂ crm:E11 Modification &amp; E65 Creation ⊂ E7 Activity. NOT a D3 Formal Derivation — D3's scope is restricted to derivations producing a "different form" of the same digital object (colour corrections, resizing, format conversions); a matcher producing identity assertions does not fit that semantic. D10 is the correct general parent for "software ran and produced output." Carries run-reproducibility metadata (run_id, parameters_hash, reviewer_status, etc.) as Hapi-namespaced properties — those properties have no declared CRM relationship and are ignored by strict readers, which is intentional.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdfs:Class>

  <rdfs:Class rdf:about="#MatcherAlgorithm">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Matcher algorithm</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/D14_Software"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The matcher algorithm definition (e.g. normalized_name_v1) — the code or procedure that gets executed. IS-A chain: hapi:MatcherAlgorithm ⊂ crmdig:D14 Software ⊂ D1 Digital Object ⊂ crm:E73 Information Object. Long-lived; many hapi:MatcherRun instances reference one hapi:MatcherAlgorithm via crmdig:L23_used_software_or_firmware.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdfs:Class>

  <rdfs:Class rdf:about="#SourceData">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Source data file</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:subClassOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/extensions/crmdig/D1_Digital_Object"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A reconciled.jsonl file or other digital input/output of a matcher run. IS-A chain: hapi:SourceData ⊂ crmdig:D1 Digital Object ⊂ crm:E73 Information Object. Referenced from hapi:MatcherRun via crmdig:L10_had_input (input data the matcher consumed) and crmdig:L11_had_output (output data the matcher produced). L10/L11 are D7-level properties inherited by D10; we deliberately do NOT use L21/L22 (D3-specific properties for "version-of" derivations).</rdfs:comment>
  </rdfs:Class>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Properties: matcher provenance
       ============================================================ -->

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#derived_by_run">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">derived by run</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:domain rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E13_Attribute_Assignment"/>
    <rdfs:range  rdf:resource="#MatcherRun"/>
    <rdfs:subPropertyOf rdf:resource="http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P15_was_influenced_by"/>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Attaches an E13 Attribute Assignment to the hapi:MatcherRun (CRMdig D10 Software Execution) that produced it. Declared rdfs:subPropertyOf crm:P15_was_influenced_by — strict CIDOC readers interpret this as "the assignment was influenced by the software-execution event." Hapi readers interpret it more specifically as "the assignment was produced by this matcher run." Domain (E13) is in P15's domain via E13 ⊂ E7. Range (hapi:MatcherRun) is in P15's range via hapi:MatcherRun ⊂ D10 ⊂ D7 ⊂ E11/E65 ⊂ E7 ⊂ ... ⊂ E1 (all chains in CRM/CRMdig RDFS).</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <!-- ============================================================
       Hapi predicates referenced from the predicate registry
       (E55 Type instances pointed at by P177_assigned_property_of_type)

       Each entry below either:
         (a) declares a rdfs:subPropertyOf relationship to a CRM property,
             with domain/range narrowing within the parent's, OR
         (b) is left as a free-standing rdf:Property when no CRM property
             has a sufficiently-tight semantic fit.

       The "no clean superproperty" cases are not deviations — CIDOC's open
       extension model permits new properties without subsumption. They ARE
       opaque to strict readers, which is acknowledged: those readers see
       the triple but don't reason on it.

       Identifying tighter CRM superproperties for each (where possible) is
       an Egyptological + CRM-modelling cross-cut and a follow-up to ADR-018.
       ============================================================ -->

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#same_entity_as">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">same entity as</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Asserts that two per-source entity nodes refer to the same real-world person/site/etc. Symmetric. No clean CRM superproperty in core 7.1.3 — CRMinf (Argumentation Model) extension may offer a tighter fit in future. Currently a free-standing Hapi property; strict readers see the triple but do not reason on it.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#in_dynastic_period">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">in dynastic period</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Assigns a Ruler (E21 Person) to a Dynasty (E4 Period) — chronological assignment, not family-membership. No clean core-CRM superproperty identified in this pass. Naive candidates (e.g. P10_falls_within) require intermediate modelling decisions about how a Person relates to a Period in time — most plausibly via the Person's reign or birth as a separate temporal entity that falls within the Dynasty's Time-Span — and the right shape is a follow-up Egyptological + CRM-modelling decision rather than an immediate subsumption call. Free-standing for now.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <!--
       Burial predicates: pragmatic Hapi-domain extensions.

       The four predicates below (tomb_owner, original_burial_in, cache_context_at,
       shares_tomb_with) connect a :Ruler (E21 Person) directly to a :Site (E27 Site).
       This is genuinely a Hapi-domain extension, not a workaround: CIDOC core has
       no clean superproperty whose domain accepts E18/E21 AND whose range accepts
       E27 Site. The closest candidate, P53_has_former_or_current_location, has
       domain E18 (which E21 satisfies via E21 ⊂ E20 ⊂ E19 ⊂ E18) but range E53
       Place — and E27 Site is NOT IS-A E53 (E27 ⊂ E26 ⊂ E18). So a direct
       subPropertyOf P53 would escape its range, which the "narrow not violate"
       rule forbids. Free-standing is the honest classification.

       Different rigour levels exist in heritage practice. CRMarchaeo (the official
       CIDOC archaeology extension at https://cidoc-crm.org/crmarchaeo/) explicitly
       materialises excavation, stratigraphy, and interment as first-class events.
       Museum-catalog CIDOC implementations generally use direct shortcuts when the
       use-case is "show me objects associated with X" rather than "reconstruct the
       burial stratigraphy." Both are valid CIDOC practice; the choice is project-
       dependent. Our matching use-case is the former; we use the shortcuts.

       Each of the four predicates below captures a structurally distinct relationship
       (commissioning, primary burial, secondary cache reburial, joint burial) and
       each would have its own rigorous-modelling shape in CRMarchaeo. We do not
       attempt to summarise those rigorous shapes here — they are out of scope for
       this manifest and best consulted in CRMarchaeo directly when archaeological-
       rigour use-cases emerge. The Hapi predicates here and any future rigorous
       chain can coexist.
  -->

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#tomb_owner">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">tomb owner</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The Ruler the tomb was commissioned for (stable across cache reburials). Distinct from original_burial_in (the ruler whose body was first interred) — a tomb may have an owner who is never interred there (Hatshepsut's KV20 partial occupancy, recut tombs). A pragmatic Hapi-domain predicate, free-standing for the reasons in the block comment above.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#original_burial_in">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">original burial in</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The Ruler whose body was first interred in this Site. Distinct from tomb_owner (the ruler the tomb was commissioned for) and from cache_context_at (secondary re-burial). A pragmatic Hapi-domain predicate, free-standing for the reasons in the block comment above.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#cache_context_at">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">cache context at</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Records a secondary burial location (Dynasty 21 priestly reburials at KV35, TT320/DB320). Distinct from tomb_owner and original_burial_in. A pragmatic Hapi-domain predicate, free-standing.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#shares_tomb_with">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">shares tomb with</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">Symmetric relation between two Rulers buried in the same Site. A pragmatic Hapi-domain predicate, free-standing.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#display_name">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">display name</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">The canonical Anglicised display form for a Ruler (ADR-016). Closest CRM superproperty under review: P1_is_identified_by (E1 → E41 Appellation) with the value being an E41 Appellation node. Pending registry-loader implementation that materialises the E41 nodes.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#reign_period">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">reign period</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A Ruler's reign as an E52 Time-Span. No clean core-CRM superproperty identified in this pass. The CIDOC-faithful approach materialises the reign itself as a separate temporal entity (likely E7 Activity or E4 Period — a reign is an extended action carried out by a ruler over a coherent period, not a modification of a physical thing), with that entity carrying P4_has_time-span to an E52. The right specific class is a follow-up modelling decision. Free-standing for now.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

  <rdf:Property rdf:about="#horus_name">
    <rdfs:label xml:lang="en">Horus name</rdfs:label>
    <rdfs:comment xml:lang="en">A Ruler's Horus titulary element. Closest CRM superproperty under review: P1_is_identified_by (E1 → E41), with the value being an E41 Appellation subclass typed for Horus-name semantics. Pending.</rdfs:comment>
  </rdf:Property>

</rdf:RDF>
